				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Q. and A.: Nicholas R. Lardy on Markets and the State in China</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By David Barboza			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-05-15T09:56:00+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">May 15, 2015 5:56 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">May 15, 2015 5:56 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/05/15/world/15sino-lardy04/15sino-lardy04-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/05/15/world/15sino-lardy04/15sino-lardy04-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/05/15/world/15sino-lardy04/15sino-lardy04-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000003685985" width="592" height="395" alt="A worker cutting steel bars at a plant in Ganyu, Jiangsu Province."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="395"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">A worker cutting steel bars at a plant in Ganyu, Jiangsu Province.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> China Daily/Reuters</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//sinosphere.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/05/15/q-and-a-nicholas-r-lardy-on-markets-and-the-state-in-china/" data-title="Q. and A.: Nicholas R. Lardy on Markets and the State in China" data-description="The economist argues that Chinaâs economic boom has been fueled by private enterprise and policies that have allowed the market to play a greater role.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Chinaâs biggest companies are still, for the most part, state-owned enterprises, or S.O.E.s. Companies controlled by the Chinese government dominate energy, finance and telecommunications, and they often have better access to capital from state-run banks. But in his latest book, âMarkets Over Mao: The Rise of Private Business in China,â the economist <a title="Biography. " href="//www.iie.com/staff/author_bio.cfm?author_id=24">Nicholas R. Lardy</a> argues that Chinaâs economic boom has been fueled by private enterprise and policies that have allowed the market to play a greater role.</p>
<div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/05/15/world/15sino-lardy01/15sino-lardy01-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/05/15/world/15sino-lardy01/15sino-lardy01-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/05/15/world/15sino-lardy01/15sino-lardy01-articleInline.jpg" id="100000003685850" width="190" height="293" alt="Nicholas R. Lardy"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="293"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Nicholas R. Lardy</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Courtesy of Nicholas R. Lardy</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">While conceding that the government has often backed initiatives aimed at strengthening the state sector, Mr. Lardy, a scholar at the <a title="Institute website." href="//www.iie.com/">Peterson Institute for International Economics</a> in Washington, argues that state companies have generally performed poorly and been a drag on economic growth, particularly in recent years. It is private enterprises, he says, that are fueling the greatest economic boom in modern history.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In an interview, Mr. Lardy dismissed the notion that China had developed a unique form of âstate capitalism.â State-run entities, in terms of their performance, are getting weaker, he said, and Chinaâs leaders, including President Xi Jinping, seem determined to embark on another round of liberalization that will cede even more ground to the private sector. Excerpts follow:</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>The prevailing wisdom about China is that its economy is dominated by the government and huge state companies. Is this wrong?</strong><span id="more-31321"></span></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">China began its economic reforms with an economy in which every metric was completely state-controlled. While the share of output originating in state-owned firms has declined quite dramatically, the state sector does remain larger than that in other capitalist economies, largely because certain industries remain off limits for private firms. If the government is able to implement the policies that the Communist Party endorsed in the fall of 2013, notably opening up parts of the economy that long have been reserved for state firms â financial services, telecommunications, the upstream oil and gas industry and civil aviation â the role of the state sector will shrink further.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>After 2002, did the Chinese authorities really reverse course and, rather than privatize and downsize the state part of the economy, roll back the reforms and start promoting the growth of state-owned companies at the expense of the private sector?</strong></p>
<div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/05/15/world/15sino-lardy02/15sino-lardy02-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/05/15/world/15sino-lardy02/15sino-lardy02-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/05/15/world/15sino-lardy02/15sino-lardy02-articleInline.jpg" id="100000003685853" width="190" height="289" alt=""   /><meta itemprop="height" content="289"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> </span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In 2003, the Chinese government created the State Asset Supervision and Administration Commission [S.A.S.A.C.], which was charged with transforming the largest state-owned companies into national champions. In a complement to this initiative, a few years later the government announced policies to promote what it called âindigenous innovation,â and later it identified several âstrategic emerging industriesâ that were to receive tax rebates and other financial incentives. Despite the multiple advantages that state firms enjoyed as a result of these policies, the firms under the S.A.S.A.C. actually underperformed. Yes, their profits increased in absolute terms but not as a share of the profits of all nonfinancial corporations. More importantly, the efficiency with which these firms used capital â a measure called return on assets â actually fell sharply. By 2013 these firmsâ return on assets had fallen to a level substantially below the cost of capital, demonstrating that, as a group, S.A.S.A.C. firms were actually a substantial drag on Chinaâs economic growth. The economy would have grown much faster in the decade starting in 2003 if the resources available to these firms had been invested in private firms.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong> Is the government still pushing in this direction, determined to create a bigger and stronger state sector?</strong></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The policies adopted by the Communist Party in the fall of 2013 suggest it has learned that picking winning firms and industries to promote economic growth is much more difficult than it appears. Rather than relying on government-formulated industrial policies, the party in 2013 said that the market âmust be the decisive factor in determining the allocation of resources.â The party also said that there must be a level playing field, that competition must be promoted and that all but natural monopolies should be eliminated. These statements suggest that the party welcomes successful firms, regardless of ownership. This is hardly surprising. The legitimacy of the party derives in large part from the rising living standards generated by economic growth. Since the evidence shows private firms are more efficient, the party gradually dismantled many of the obstacles holding back the expansion of private firms.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>How significantly are private companies outperforming state-run companies in China?</strong></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">To date, in industries in which private firms have been allowed to enter, S.O.E.s have been largely displaced, mostly because they are less efficient and thus have smaller retained earnings. Since most investment in China is financed from retained earnings, on average state firms have been unable to keep up with private firms. For example, a few decades ago, steel was produced only by state-owned companies. Today the stateâs share of steel production is down to a third. Private firms in the steel industry on average are far more efficient, have much larger retained earnings, and thus are able to finance more investment than state companies. The combination of more investment and more efficient use of resources has propelled private steel company output to a level twice that of state companies.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">One of the best-kept secrets about most of Chinaâs biggest S.O.E.s is their poor performance, even in sectors where entry by private players has been forbidden and a handful of state firms are completely dominant. Yes, the profits of these state firms are huge in absolute terms. But, relative to the assets that the firms control, their returns are paltry at best.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Why doesnât China seem to have its own global brands?<br />
</strong></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Few countries at Chinaâs level of per capita income have developed globally recognized brands. But several Chinese firms can now be regarded as national champions. Huawei would be one. Its sales in 2014 were $46 billion, of which almost two-thirds were international. The firm does business in over 170 countries. This is an amazing transformation for a company that was founded less than 30 years ago and won its first contract outside the mainland [in Hong Kong] in 1997.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Do you see the Chinese authorities lifting restrictions and opening up more parts of the economy that have long been closed to the private sector and foreign companies, such as finance, energy, education, media or health care?</strong></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">China is already liberalizing some of these sectors, by allowing the creation of truly private banks, hospitals, schools and airlines. The new competition these private firms will bring to the market will force state companies and institutions in these domains to step up their game or lose market share to the new private players. In either case, the winners in this process will be Chinese consumers. However, it seems unlikely that the party will allow much liberalization of the media.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>How have multinational corporations performed in China?</strong></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">There are many examples of foreign companies â including American companies â that have been successful selling directly to Chinese consumers. Nike sales in China have been running about $2.5 billion in recent years and jumped by almost 20 percent in the first quarter of 2015. Starbucks has almost 1,400 locations in China, and its current expansion plan will soon make China its second-largest market after the United States. U.S. fast food companies, including McDonald&#8217;s and Yum Brands [KFC, Taco Bell and Pizza Hut], have enjoyed extraordinary success in China. Yum is Chinaâs most successful restaurant chain, with more than 6,700 restaurants in over 1,000 Chinese cities. Foreign retailers, including Walmart, Tesco, Carrefour and Metro, account for about 15 percent of Chinaâs retail sales, currently running at more than $4 trillion, a sharp contrast with other large Asian countries, such as Japan and India, where so-called big-box foreign retailers are mostly shut out of the market.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong> In the May/June 2015 issue of Foreign Affairs magazine, Chen Zhiwu, who teaches finance at Yale University, wrote that China still has a huge number of state-owned companies, and that the authorities&#8217; plan is not to privatize them but to allow private companies to invest in those state entities, which could make S.O.E.s even bigger. Isnât that a sign that state sector is not about to shrink?</strong></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">China has about 8.3 million corporate enterprises, of which 280,000 are state-owned, 6,550,000 are private and the balance are foreign and collective firms and a residual category of other. China began selling minority stakes in S.O.E.s to private investors, both domestic and foreign, more than a decade ago. In some cases these firms adopted various aspects of modern corporate governance, and their economic performance improved somewhat. But this process did not significantly slow the gradual reduction in the share of output produced in state-owned firms, and it is unlikely to do so now. Moreover, there is some indication that asset sales to private players under the Xi Jinping-Li Keqiang leadership will go further, eventually putting private entrepreneurs in control of some of these state firms.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Where are Chinaâs reforms headed? Is China really moving toward a system that will be indistinguishable from that of the United States or Western Europe? </strong></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Capitalism comes in many variants. French capitalism in the early 1980s, when the Mitterrand government nationalized major industrial groups and the 36 largest banks, is very different from the French capitalism that emerged after several waves of privatizations beginning in 1986. And even today the role of the state in France is substantially larger than in the U.S. So while China has been moving toward a more capitalist economy for decades, there should be no presumption that its economic system eventually will be indistinguishable either from that of the United States or that of France. But for now and the foreseeable future, capital efficiency and productivity are the focus of Chinaâs leadership, and it is clear that to achieve that, the enhancement of market forces, by allowing private firms to compete on a level playing field with state firms, is the way to go.</p>
	</div>
